<br>
How do I know this?  I have on numerous occasionsions used this very gambit to powerlevel my wife's rogue.  I would remove my weapons and put an idol in my primary hand.  I would not engage autoattack.  I would approach a mob that normally would not attack me and taunt.  If i taunted once she would take the mob off me after about 50-100 points of damage.  If i taunted a few times to start, and then continued to taunt the mob would stay on me solidly much longer.  Once she passed me on the hatelist (usually 1/3 to 1/2 way though the mobs life) I could no longer hold aggro without attacking.  I could however taunt to spin the mob for a well timed backstab.  This had to be timed however as she would need to backstab before she did about 50 damag normally.  Sometimes the mob would jsut ignore me and beat on her (failed taunt).<br>
<br>
I have seen that a sucessful taunt adds some aggro even if you are at the top of the list.  It may be insignificant if you have fancy hate weapons and high dps. but it might be useful to some warriors.  I am suspicious that a failed taunt attemp also adds some aggro, but haven't explicitly tested this.<br>
<br>
Now if you are really having aggro problems, and especially if you are a masher, get an instant cast self buff item.  Jboots work, but the 8th and 9th rings work much better.  Spam those to create extra aggro.  I tested this with an enchanter friend.  It takes about a dozen clicks of damage shield to equal 1 tash.  This works up close and at range.  I have brought mobs off my cleric on to me using nothing but this ring( I was testing while botting).  It works because it is a buff, and you are ont he hate list.  When you buff someone on the hatelist you gain hate, much like if you heal them.  <br>
<br>
If you use the clicks some people will bitch about the spam and the lag.  Jboots are very little lag but the ring is alot.  But then it only causes lag if they have spell particles on.  <br>
<br>
Ok, that's enough rambling from me. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=252504" target="top">Xath Carnage</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhick>Rhick</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/14/03 3:18:20 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_atk.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ~</span><hr size=1> I am a ranger and my taunt sucks... that said I've done some tests on taunt. <br>
<br>
I pulled a goranga gatherer in Maiden's eye and snared it 20 times. Then I had a 60 warrior friend taunt the mob without attacking. He taunted.. and taunted, and taunted, all told he taunted 20 times. I wasn't attacking and he wasn't attacking, but the mob would not turn to him. (Yes his skill was maxed) However if I moved out of melee range the mob turned.  I moved back into melee range and the mob stayed on him. Note that we did no damage at all during this time. We were not wielding weapons to ensure that riposte damage didn't contaminate results.<br>
<br>
This suggests that to turn a mob you have to achieve some amount of hate over the highest person on list.  This presumably prevents a mob from bouncing aggro back and forth when 2 people are equal in hate.<br>
<br>
However it was clear to me that taunt alone added a very insignificant amount of hate. He hit taunt 20 times, and still did not generate enough aggy to turn the mob.  Yes that was 2 minutes of taunting, and my warrior friend was very discouraged at the end of it.<br>
<br>
Again I snared 20 times to pull, but this time my warrior friend taunted aggro off me with a single taunt while I kited (I was never in melee range so proximity aggro+taunt was enough to turn mob). After this a wizard was able to nuke the goranga gatherer to death without pulling aggro off the warrior. The warrior did no attack at all.<br>
<br>
Aggro transfer is a very useful tool for a warrior to hold aggro. Have your paladins and rangers chain cast spells for the first 15 seconds of a fight. Once you succesfully taunt over their aggro you can go AFK for the rest of the fight. <br>
<br>
In my opinion mashing your taunt key is a sure way to carpal tunnels and does nothing to increase your hate. Set up some scientific tests for yourself, and prove me wrong.<br>
<br>
-Rhick<br>
